Continuing with the new LEVEL OF DETAIL previously found, create an Element - Name - Value (ENV) Model in table format with 5 columns and about ten rows (approximately 10 parts into which the system is divided):
PART | ATTRIBUTE | OBJECT | PRODUCT | IDEAL PRODUCT
Analyze how each ATTRIBUTE changes during the transformation from OBJECT to PRODUCT and define the ideal value of the attribute in the IDEAL PRODUCT.
Example ENV model with different LEVEL OF DETAIL, for a hairdryer:
PART | ATTRIBUTE | OBJECT | PRODUCT | IDEAL PRODUCT
Hair | Surface moisture | Present | Absent | None
Hair | Mechanical energy applied | Absent | Moderate | None
Hair | Temperature | Ambient | Slightly variable | Unchanged (ambient temperature)
Hair | Surface integrity | Intact | Intact | Perfectly intact
Water droplet | Adhesion to hair | High | None | None
Water droplet | Position | Attached to hair | Separated from hair | Completely removed from system
Water droplet | Volume | Unchanged | Unchanged | Eliminated from area of interest
Hair–droplet interface | Adhesion force | High | Reduced to zero | None
Hair–droplet interface | Contact angle | Favorable to adhesion | Reduced | Minimum possible
Surrounding air | Velocity | None | May increase | None
Surrounding air | Dynamic pressure | None | May increase | None
Applied physical field | Intensity | Absent | Present | Minimum necessary or self-generated
Overall system | Energy consumption | None | Present | Close to zero
Overall system | Removal time | Infinite (without intervention) | Short | Instantaneous
